Comment: The Vienna Opening, an unusual offshoot of the double-KP game. White hopes to advance his KBP forward before moving his KN so as to quickly open the K-side.

Black naturally attacks the unguarded KP.
Hoping to storm through with his K-side Pawns.
Thrusting his own center Pawns forward. This position can also arise by transposition from the Falkbeer Counter Gambit [1 P-K4 P-K4 2 P-KB4 P-Q4 3 N-QB3 N-KB3].
Removing one of Reinle's central Pawns.
Bearing his Q on the weak spot, KB7.
Threatening to capture the advanced Pawn and attack Neureiter's Queen.
Countering with a threat to the exposed White Queen.
Equalizing the material while protecting the Knight.
Getting out of the line of fire.
Cleverly attacking the Queen again. And 9 QxB??? would be answered by 9... NxP ch!!!, forking the R, Q and K.
9 Q-KN3 would get the Queen out of danger, but 9... NxP ch would still fork K and R.
White resigns. His Q has no flight square.
